Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'Convolutional networks (ConvNets) have recently enjoyed a great success in large-scale image and video recognition (Krizhevsky et al., 2012; Zeiler & Fergus, 2013; Sermanet et al., 2014; Simonyan & Zisserman, 2014) which has become possible due to the large public image repositories, such as ImageNet (Deng et al., 2009), and high-performance computing systems, such as GPUs or large-scale distributed clusters (Dean et al., 2012). In particular, an important role in the advance of deep visual recognition architectures has been played by the ImageNet Large-Scale Visual Recognition Challenge (ILSVRC) (Russakovsky et al., 2014), which has served as a testbed for a few generations of large-scale image classification systems, from high-dimensional shallow feature encodings (Perronnin et al., 2010) (the winner of ILSVRC-2011) to deep ConvNets (Krizhevsky et al., 2012) (the winner of ILSVRC-2012). ', 'bbox': [169, 486, 826, 626], 'page_idx': 0}

Analysis: The content is structured as an informative passage discussing the advancements in convolutional networks (ConvNets) for image and video recognition. It includes historical references to significant studies and milestones in this field, highlighting key contributors and events, such as the ImageNet challenge. The relationships between research papers and the progress in technology, such as GPUs, are emphasized, providing context for the development of deep visual recognition. The significance lies in its presentation of how ConvNets have evolved through competitive benchmarks like ILSVRC, underlining the interplay of academic research and technological innovation. Relevant details include citation of key studies and challenges relevant for academic citations and further exploration in artificial intelligence and computer vision areas.

