Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'During training, the input to our ConvNets is a fixed-size $2 2 4 \\times 2 2 4$ RGB image. The only preprocessing we do is subtracting the mean RGB value, computed on the training set, from each pixel. The image is passed through a stack of convolutional (conv.) layers, where we use filters with a very small receptive field: $3 \\times 3$ (which is the smallest size to capture the notion of left/right, up/down, center). In one of the configurations we also utilise $1 \\times 1$ convolution filters, which can be seen as a linear transformation of the input channels (followed by non-linearity). The convolution stride is fixed to 1 pixel; the spatial padding of conv. layer input is such that the spatial resolution is preserved after convolution, i.e. the padding is 1 pixel for $3 \\times 3$ conv. layers. Spatial pooling is carried out by five max-pooling layers, which follow some of the conv. layers (not all the conv. layers are followed by max-pooling). Max-pooling is performed over a $2 \\times 2$ pixel window, with stride 2. ', 'bbox': [169, 316, 823, 458], 'page_idx': 1}

Analysis: This text content is structured in a technical manner, detailing the architecture and configuration of Convolutional Neural Networks (ConvNets) during training. The key elements include the input specifications, preprocessing steps, convolutional layer configurations, and pooling strategies. Relationships between these components highlight the importance of spatial resolution maintenance through appropriate padding and the width of filters. The significance lies in its foundational role in understanding image processing through ConvNets, especially for those engaged in deep learning and computer vision. Relevant details include parameters like filter sizes, strides, and pooling techniques, which are essential for anyone looking to reproduce or understand ConvNet structures.

