Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'A stack of convolutional layers (which has a different depth in different architectures) is followed by three Fully-Connected (FC) layers: the first two have 4096 channels each, the third performs 1000- way ILSVRC classification and thus contains 1000 channels (one for each class). The final layer is the soft-max layer. The configuration of the fully connected layers is the same in all networks. ', 'bbox': [169, 463, 823, 520], 'page_idx': 1}

Analysis: This text describes the architecture of a neural network, specifically focusing on its convolutional and fully-connected layers. The structure is organized into a series of layered components: a stack of convolutional layers followed by three Fully-Connected layers and finally a soft-max layer. Key information includes the specific number of channels in each layer, such as the first two FC layers having 4096 channels and the third with 1000 channels for ILSVRC classification. The consistency of the configuration of the fully-connected layers across different architectures is also noted. This context is significant as it provides insight into the design choices in neural networks that can affect performance in classification tasks. Relevant details for knowledge retrieval would include the specific function and configuration of each layer, the role of the soft-max layer, and the implications of having a fixed architecture in distinguishing between different classes.

