Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'All hidden layers are equipped with the rectification (ReLU (Krizhevsky et al., 2012)) non-linearity. We note that none of our networks (except for one) contain Local Response Normalisation (LRN) normalisation (Krizhevsky et al., 2012): as will be shown in Sect. 4, such normalisation does not improve the performance on the ILSVRC dataset, but leads to increased memory consumption and computation time. Where applicable, the parameters for the LRN layer are those of (Krizhevsky et al., 2012). ', 'bbox': [169, 526, 823, 611], 'page_idx': 1}

Analysis: The content is organized as a brief excerpt discussing the use of rectified linear unit (ReLU) non-linearity in neural networks. The mention of Local Response Normalisation (LRN) highlights a notable consideration in deep learning architecture. The text incorporates references to previous work (Krizhevsky et al., 2012) to support claims regarding the effects of LRN on performance and resource consumption. Key components include the assertion that LRN does not enhance performance on the ILSVRC dataset, and the implications of memory and computation trade-offs when utilizing this normalisation technique. The context emphasizes best practices in neural network design, particularly relevant for practitioners in machine learning. The text is concise but packed with critical details for evaluating neural network configurations and optimizations.

