Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'Our ConvNet configurations are quite different from the ones used in the top-performing entries of the ILSVRC-2012 (Krizhevsky et al., 2012) and ILSVRC-2013 competitions (Zeiler & Fergus, 2013; Sermanet et al., 2014). Rather than using relatively large receptive fields in the first conv. layers (e.g. $1 1 \\times 1 1$ with stride 4 in (Krizhevsky et al., 2012), or $7 \\times 7$ with stride 2 in (Zeiler & Fergus, 2013; Sermanet et al., 2014)), we use very small $3 \\times 3$ receptive fields throughout the whole net, which are convolved with the input at every pixel (with stride 1). It is easy to see that a stack of two $3 \\times 3$ conv. layers (without spatial pooling in between) has an effective receptive field of $5 \\times 5$ ; three ', 'bbox': [169, 825, 823, 925], 'page_idx': 1}

Analysis: The text discusses ConvNet configurations that differ significantly from those utilized in the successful submissions of the ILSVRC-2012 and ILSVRC-2013 competitions. The structure is organized by contrasting current approaches with previous ones, emphasizing the use of smaller receptive fields ('$3 \times 3$') for convolution layers as opposed to larger ones used in past configurations. The text highlights the effective receptive field achieved through stacking smaller convolution layers, demonstrating a nuanced understanding of deep learning architectures. This context affirms the importance of hyperparameter choices in neural network design for enhanced performance. Key components include comparisons between model configurations, the concept of receptive fields, and implications for neural network effectiveness.

