Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'The incorporation of $1 \\times 1$ conv. layers (configuration C, Table 1) is a way to increase the nonlinearity of the decision function without affecting the receptive fields of the conv. layers. Even though in our case the $1 \\times 1$ convolution is essentially a linear projection onto the space of the same dimensionality (the number of input and output channels is the same), an additional non-linearity is introduced by the rectification function. It should be noted that $1 \\times 1$ conv. layers have recently been utilised in the “Network in Network” architecture of Lin et al. (2014). ', 'bbox': [169, 750, 823, 834], 'page_idx': 2}

Analysis: The content is structured as a technical explanation regarding the use of $1 \times 1$ convolution layers in neural network architectures. It begins by stating the purpose of these layers in increasing nonlinearity without altering the receptive fields. Key elements include the mention of how $1 \times 1$ convolutions function as linear projections and how a rectification function introduces additional non-linearity. The relationship between these layers and their application in the Network in Network architecture highlights the evolving nature of deep learning techniques. This content is significant for understanding advanced neural network design and facilitates the retrieval of concepts related to convolutional layers, specifically their roles and applications in modern architectures.

Text Content Analysis:
Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'Small-size convolution filters have been previously used by Ciresan et al. (2011), but their nets are significantly less deep than ours, and they did not evaluate on the large-scale ILSVRC dataset. Goodfellow et al. (2014) applied deep ConvNets (11 weight layers) to the task of street number recognition, and showed that the increased depth led to better performance. GoogLeNet (Szegedy et al., 2014), a top-performing entry of the ILSVRC-2014 classification task, was developed independently of our work, but is similar in that it is based on very deep ConvNets ', 'bbox': [169, 839, 826, 925], 'page_idx': 2}

Analysis: The text discusses advancements in convolutional neural networks (ConvNets), focusing on comparisons between earlier models and recent developments. It organizes its content by referencing specific studies (Ciresan et al., Goodfellow et al., Szegedy et al.) and their contributions to deep learning. Key elements include the performance of deep ConvNets versus shallow networks, the significance of model depth, and benchmark datasets like ILSVRC. The relational context shows the evolution of deep learning techniques in computer vision and their impact on tasks such as street number recognition. Details relevant for knowledge retrieval include the release years of studies, the number of weight layers in models, and performance metrics related to the ILSVRC.

