Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'Since the fully-convolutional network is applied over the whole image, there is no need to sample multiple crops at test time (Krizhevsky et al., 2012), which is less efficient as it requires network re-computation for each crop. At the same time, using a large set of crops, as done by Szegedy et al. (2014), can lead to improved accuracy, as it results in a finer sampling of the input image compared to the fully-convolutional net. Also, multi-crop evaluation is complementary to dense evaluation due to different convolution boundary conditions: when applying a ConvNet to a crop, the convolved feature maps are padded with zeros, while in the case of dense evaluation the padding for the same crop naturally comes from the neighbouring parts of an image (due to both the convolutions and spatial pooling), which substantially increases the overall network receptive field, so more context is captured. While we believe that in practice the increased computation time of multiple crops does not justify the potential gains in accuracy, for reference we also evaluate our networks using 50 crops per scale ( $5 \\times 5$ regular grid with 2 flips), for a total of 150 crops over 3 scales, which is comparable to 144 crops over 4 scales used by Szegedy et al. (2014). ', 'bbox': [169, 378, 826, 559], 'page_idx': 4}

Analysis: The content is structured around the discussion of fully-convolutional networks and their efficiency in image processing tasks. It compares the use of single evaluation versus multiple crop evaluations during the testing phase. Key elements include references to works by Krizhevsky et al. (2012) and Szegedy et al. (2014), the implications of padding in convolutional networks, and the trade-offs between accuracy and computation time. The relationships between single and multiple crop evaluations are explored in the context of network receptive fields, with specific details on crop configurations for performance assessment. This text is significant as it addresses optimization strategies in deep learning models for image classification tasks, providing relevant insights for researchers in computer vision.

