Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'Settings comparison. As can be seen from Table 8, per-class regression (PCR) outperforms the class-agnostic single-class regression (SCR), which differs from the findings of Sermanet et al. (2014), where PCR was outperformed by SCR. We also note that fine-tuning all layers for the localisation task leads to noticeably better results than fine-tuning only the fully-connected layers (as done in (Sermanet et al., 2014)). In these experiments, the smallest images side was set to $S = 3 8 4$ ; the results with $S = 2 5 6$ exhibit the same behaviour and are not shown for brevity. ', 'bbox': [169, 253, 825, 337], 'page_idx': 10}

Analysis: The content is structured around a settings comparison for regression methods in a machine learning context, specifically discussing per-class regression (PCR) and single-class regression (SCR). It highlights key findings from empirical results presented in Table 8, noting that PCR outperforms SCR, contrasting with previous research by Sermanet et al. (2014). The analysis also emphasizes the impact of fine-tuning layers in the localization task, indicating that fine-tuning all layers gives better results than limiting to fully-connected layers. The mention of image sizes ($S = 384$ and $S = 256$) provides relevant experimental conditions, aiding in knowledge retrieval for similar studies.

