Content: {'type': 'text', 'text': 'Comparison with the state of the art. We compare our best localisation result with the state of the art in Table 10. With $2 5 . 3 \\%$ test error, our “VGG” team won the localisation challenge of ILSVRC-2014 (Russakovsky et al., 2014). Notably, our results are considerably better than those of the ILSVRC-2013 winner Overfeat (Sermanet et al., 2014), even though we used less scales and did not employ their resolution enhancement technique. We envisage that better localisation performance can be achieved if this technique is incorporated into our method. This indicates the performance advancement brought by our very deep ConvNets – we got better results with a simpler localisation method, but a more powerful representation. ', 'bbox': [169, 739, 826, 852], 'page_idx': 10}

Analysis: The content is structured as a comparative analysis between the author's localisation results and the state of the art in the field, specifically highlighted in Table 10. It conveys key information regarding the performance of the 'VGG' team in the ILSVRC-2014 challenge, with a specific test error metric provided. The relationship between the author's results and past work (Overfeat) emphasizes the evolution of localisation techniques in image recognition. The context of this comparison points to the significance of innovation in deep learning architectures (ConvNets) and the potential for further improvement with additional techniques. This detail is critical for understanding advancements in localisation methods in computer vision.

